What, the way the US administration did in the 1980s- with men like Wolfowitz, Cheney and Rumsfeld in the Reagan cabinet?  These are the last people to lecture us on duplicitious evasion, they're experts in the practice.<br>
<br>
I'd also add:  Codswallop.  With that kind of reasoning there is no legitimate criticism possible of government policy in any field.  With that kind of reasoning speaking out against McCarthy in the 1950s was &quot;supporting the evil commies!&quot;.  Similarly, anyone who spoke out against government policy in the 1960s was supporting the agenda of civil rights demonstraters- I suppose anti-Vietnam war protesters were wrong to speak out too?  It's only a shame they didn't speak out sooner- a quarter of a million Americans and two million Vietnamese lives might have been spared.  If policies are blatantly wrong in their approach (sup pre-emption) and will encourage terrorist activity (a far bigger threat than rogue states)- then why on earth shouldn't I speak out against something that affects us all so profoundly?  <br>
<br>
What you're effectively saying is that either I'm with you or against you- sorry, but I don't buy that.  The world isn't divided into black and white, good and evil.  If I see a policy that threatens our security being put forward by the Bush administration, I will speak out against it.  If, in denying terrorist groups another reason to mobilize against us I'm seen by you as &quot;supporting Saddam&quot;- then that's something I'll gladly accept, erroneous and nonsensical as I find it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You may not want to, but you are making his case for him<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Ha, that's hilarious.  By speaking out against a harmful policy that could well destroy the foundation of international consensus I'm somehow supporting a bloodthirsty dictator?  You'll have to explain that one to me...I don't follow your reasoning there at all.  <br>
<br>
If what you're trying to say is that the disarmament process is being delayed somewhat by Sadaam and that it's taking slightly longer than it should- then my question to you is:  so bloody what?  If the inspectors, the experts on the ground say they are able to continue their work relatively unhindered, then who the devil are we or our governments to question their opinion?  Sadaam isn't a threat- he's being deterred and contained by the overwhelming force the UK and US governments have deployed in the region.  Enough nuclear weapons to destroy the entirety of the Middle East ten times over is within easy striking distance.  Saddam's regime isn't a suicidal one- and inspections are working- so where is the case for war Kadandrum?  The answer is that there isn't one- the threat of force is producing results- not comprehensive results- but where's the almighty rush?<br>
<br>
The inspectors should have as much time as they feel they need to do their job properly.  If they come back to the UNSC and say- &quot;Sorry, we're unable to do our work, there isn't enough cooperation to proceed with disarmament&quot; in clear and uncertain terms- then I will support military action.  Until the diplomatic route has been exhausted Kadandrum, I don't see why anyone should.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>He's playing the UN showing that it truly is a worthless world government incapable of dealing with anything except minor regional conflicts<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Read my last post and then tell me again with a straight face that the UN is a &quot;worthless world government&quot;.  As for &quot;playing the UN&quot;- all countries are guilty of that- when Yemen decided not to back the US position in 1991, 70 million dollars was slashed off their aid budget.  Representatives from your government and mine are currently arm-twisting Angola, Pakistan and Cameroon to fall into line for the next resolution.  Fact remains- it is the only credible international institution that is perceived as impartial.  Despite its failings, it is the best forum for diplomacy in history, especially since the end of the Cold War.  And it is here that we and the US in particular need support to win the war on terror.  How do you think the next terrorist attack will be prevented Kad?  The only sure way you have is international cooperation amongst intelligence agencies, police forces, and the governments in charge of them.  And it's not going to be easy to get that cooperation from the people you need it from most if you ignore international institutions- I've said it before in all my posts, but people keep refusing to acknowledge it.  Ignoring a crucially relevant point like that doesn't make it any less true.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I find it simply amazing that a council of governments, elected by no one mind you and in turn not accountable to the electorate, with a myriad of interests that they are beholden to, can usurp the sovereignty of a country by giving a handful of socialist countries absolute veto power<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Good god, what drivel...where to begin.  How about by pointing out the obvious- most governments in the United Nations are elected and at the very least fully representative.  Even governments that are unelected need to be dealt with- if people only practiced diplomacy with nations they got along with, we'd be back to a hundred years ago with power blocs forever poised on the brink of war.  <br>
<br>
Also, the fact that 10 members of the security council are rotated rather than elected (at that nation's own choice mind you)- doesn't detract one bit from their effectiveness.  Electoral systems often have far less credibility for me than appointed positions.  Case in point- how much credibility do you think a lot of your fellow citizens had in the electoral college system after the last presidential election Kad?  The man with the most votes lost- and the final run-off was farcically decided by the brother of one of the candidates- surely a conflict of interest.  My point is simple- a Supreme Court Justice in the US or a Chief Justice in this country are NOT elected...but I would trust the institution they stand for far more than the one Bush stands for, given the way the election was conducted vis a vis the appointment.<br>
<br>
As for the &quot;myriad of interests&quot;- I should bloody well hope so- a single dictatorial position is far less preferable surely.  If you love freedom and democracy- the clash of ideals in a civilized atmosphere- you can't help but believe in the UN.  The US is *part* of the UN Kad- you can't talk about them as seperate entities.  In fact, the US is the most powerful member of the UN, a co-founder and a signatory to its charter and declaration of human rights.  As a key member of the UN- the Bush administration needs to engage with it, not dictate policy to it. <br>
<br>
Now to something you said that offends me- a handful of socialist countries given veto power?  First off- what the devil are you talking about?  The UNSC and the UN itself were formed by these 5 countries, the victors after WWII- no one *gave* them veto power, they agreed by consensus that they themselves should have it.  Next, you rubbish the UK and France as &quot;socialist countries&quot;.  Sorry to spoil the party, but I'm actually quite glad I live in a country that's pursued socialism as a cornerstone of public spending.  My children no matter the size of their wallets or social background will have guaranteed education up to and including university, health care, social services and public transport of a high standard- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>free at the point of delivery</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Doctors instead of insurance companies in charge of my health, considerbly less judgement of a person's worth as defined by their income and greater social justice for the poor and disadvantaged.  If the price of pursuing that system is slightly less competitive business, then I'll take that instead of WorldCom/Enron thank you very much.  <br>
<br>
I'd rather my tax money was spent on those things rather than defence to be perfectly honest.  Since the end of World War II America have spent 19 trillion dollars on what they call “defense”.  Which they spell differently.  And define very differently!  If you were to spend $26m every day since the birth of Christ, you would have spent less than the Americans have spent on defence since the end of the Second World war.  If you were to spend a tenth of a penny for every one of those defence dollars- that would have fed and clothed the world's starving in the same time period fifty times over.  At a time when the world economy is faltering and the spectre of terrorism threatens us all- from Bali to Baltimore and London to Lucknow- why is this costly and detrimental war being pursued by the Bush administration.  A fraction of that cost spent on intelligence and police resources would be better spent- a fraction of that spent building a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>willing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> international coalition to fight terrorism would make us all safer.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why should a country scede their sovereignty to the UN? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A very important and pertinent question for any nation- it has just as important and significant an answer.  First of all, because it's a good idea, it makes sense.  Why does the US sign environmental concessions to reduce pollution (except Kyoto, but a lot have been signed)?  Because it secures a better planet for future generations.  Every time a country commits itself to a treaty it surrenders its sovreignity- for something it believes in.<br>
<br>
You indirectly pose the question- what good is the UN and what do we get out of it?  Credibility, trust and a platform for peace is the answer.  Credibility- individual nations lack it desperately.  Bush and Blair will *never* solve the Israel-Palestine conflict on their own, their present policy is unconditional support for one of the two sides.  They just don't have the credibility to solve that crisis- Israel is in violation of 64 UNSC resolutions, *all* telling it to pull back to pre-1967 borders.  Until that issue is satisfactorily resolved, none of us are safe from the threat of terror, and without that international credibility we will never have that.  <br>
<br>
Next:  Trust.  There is deep distrust of individual nations meddling in other countrys' affairs.  From colonial states carving up the cake of Africa and drawing lines in the sand in the Middle East- to US and USSR willingness to set up surrogate states facing each other- individual nations cannot possibly be trusted to do the right thing.  The UN brings multilateral credibility to a solution- and a willingness to see it from both sides, more or less free of the confines of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>single</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> nation's interests.  It is a forum for cooperation that has accomplished great things- and it is the only platform we have to build consensus and fight terrorism with.<br>
<br>
Lastly- it's a platform for peace.  Without a forum to discuss and resolve issues before they flame up into conflict, the world fought bloody and terrible wars.  From the Napoleonic wars, to the Crimean war to two world wars, costing millions of lives- nations drew an important lesson.  That if there was an institution set up designed to tackle disputes and resolve them before the bullets started flying, lives could be saved and conflicts avoided.  Without the UN we'd see a war a week and a world war a decade.  Deterrence, containment and aggressive diplomacy are its teeth- with force to be used as a last resort.  These three measures of containment, deterrence and diplomacy are producing results.  Force can <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be used at some stage in the future.  Diplomatic positions and stances can be reversed in the blink of an eye- but you can't put the use of force genie back into the proverbial bottle.  <br>
<br>
And that is why the US and other countries <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>did</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cede a portion of their sovreignity by signing the UN charter.  It is also why any military action should be in accordance with international law.  The US/UK administrations have permanent members seats and are making the case for war to 13 other nations.  Now if there is a case for war, they'll win the argument, pass a resolution and we go to war.  If people aren't convinced, and say the experts should decide for themselves when they can't continue their work, then that's what should be done, simple as that.  <br>
<br>
Read my last posts carefully Kadandrum- call it dissent if you will- but actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>read it</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Simply telling me I'm a dissenter accomplishes nothing, it's name-calling.  Dissenter, pacifist hippie, art poufta, anarchist- they're just names and stereotypes- I'm none of those things in position.  If you think there's a case for war instead of containment- let's hear it.  I've certainly heard nothing from my government or the US government that makes the case- if anyone thinks they can do better I'm all ears.  We all want to feel safer after 11/9- attacking Saddam isn't the way to do it- if anyone thinks I'm wrong on that, let's hear why.  Saying I shouldn't be speaking my mind isn't debate, it's a dismissal of the issues raised.  Exactly how wise is it to dismiss these arguments when pursuit of this policy would bring about disastrous consequences?<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
