<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
How about we start by being absolutely *clear* about the source of this dispute.  The point of dispute is to do with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Weapons of Mass Destruction or WMD</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The issue is NOT about whether Saddam's regime is preserved or not.  Let's be absolutely clear about this- there are lots and lots of unsavoury regimes in the world- going around toppling heads of state is not practical, realistic and will create far more problems than it solves.  Say, the possible collapse of international law and a whole list of treaties connected with the UN charter?  It's also a policy of pre-emption founded on fears, suspicions and possible threats.  Rather than good intelligence of clear and imminent threats- you have superpowers acting as judge jury and executioner with insufficient information.  I can think of no better way to destroy the world order and throw the door wide open for terrorists.<br>
<br>
The sensible alternative is to engage these regimes and soften their approach with diplomacy rather than threats. This approach is working in China, Myanmar, Russia and other repressive states- it takes time, patience and adherence.  Not a quick in-out and left out to dry a la Afghanistan.  It's vital that if military action ultimately proves necessary that there are plans to reconstruct the shattered infrastructure. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I do not know how much clearly I can make the point that dissenters, with intention or not, are helping to preserve Hussein's regime &lt;snip&gt; ...But that is the way of our society and our rules. So be it. I just wish people would see the consequences of their words<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh I see- my posting on this messageboard helps preserve his regime.  You're saying I take it, that Saddam might be cynically exploiting my altruistic arguments by reading this message board and pandering to key nations' representatives opposing this war.  Who also read this message board, amazing!  Hey Saddam- if you're reading this board- cooperate 100% k?  Not 60 or 70%, that last 30% seems to be awfully important for some reason.  Oh, and if any other amazingly important diplomats are reading this- I'm sure you all know Saddam is an evil repressive dictator, but that dealing diplomatically with him saves lives and effects peaceful change.<br>
<br>
Returning to the real world for a moment, why is anyone who favours a peaceful path to disarmament a &quot;dissenter&quot;?  As I said, name-calling gets us nowhere.  On the other hand,  people with the moral character to advocate force as a last resort- if by labeling them &quot;dissenters&quot; you salve your consience re:  the innocents inevitably killed in a war you advocate, then feel free.  In a civilised exchange of views there should be no need to label people as &quot;warmongers&quot;, &quot;hippies&quot; or &quot;dissenters&quot;.  The term itself is completely subjective- if I wanted to apply it to you dissenting from a peaceful path to disarmament (what most of the world wants)- then I could.  However, I choose not to, it adds nothing to the debate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In fact, he is counting on YOU to help delay military action.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why do I feel like I'm banging my head against a brick wall here?  Let me be blunt:  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Military action should not be our primary goal- our goal should be to avoid it and disarm peacefully</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Yes that's right- military action as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>last</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> resort instead of shooting first and asking questions later- what a novel concept that is!  I want peaceful disarmament, and so does any sane individual on the planet.  I don't care how long it takes- there's no flaming rush is there?  Saddam is being contained, he's a rabid dog in a bloody effective cage of military hardware and personnel.  He has 0 airspace, electronic surveillance painting his country like a christmas tree and inspectors patrolling his factories- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>there is no imminent danger</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.   <br>
<br>
As long as Blix and El Baradei, the experts on the ground with the relevant information at their fingertips- as long as they believe peaceful disarmament is possible and achievable then that's what we ought to do.  I've said it once, I've said it a thousand times- if they come back and say <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;We can't do our job any more&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> then I'll back military action.  If that were to happen then the peaceful route will have been exhausted, and the war can go ahead in all its glory, collateral damage *cough* I mean civilian casualties and all.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But isn't that what dissenters want after all? A peaceful solution? Right, thanks for allying with the enemy<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A peaceful road to disarmament is allying with the enemy?  I'm nearly speechless to be honest, don't know whether to laugh or cry.  You seem to think that war is the beginning and the end of the solution- nay- the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>only</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> solution to this crisis, you make peaceful solutions sound like failure.  If peace is your true enemy Kad, then I can only pity you.  <br>
<br>
Submitted with equal respect,<br>
<br>
