Sorry, the vein of your last post lead me to believe that you didn't believe in the idea of peaceful disarmament.  Simple misunderstanding, my apologies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'll tell you why. Sadamm is playing a game of international chicken where, if he can show partial compliance (destroying six (!) al-Samoun missiles in one day? WTF is that? There are hundreds of them and it takes a whole day to destroy six?) he buys time<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I put the question again- what does it matter how long disarmament takes as long as it is peaceful?  We both acknowledge and accept that he is being effectively contained and deterred- in his present situation there is no possible circumstance in which he could pose a threat.  So the issue of time is a moot one, for this and other reasons.  Give the inspectors as much time as they want while they feel they can do their job- it's not as if Saddam is going anywhere.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And time works in your favor when a force of several thousand are sitting at your door step and in a matter of weeks the temperature, where these forces are located, will reach 120 degrees.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Heh, I find it interesting that experts have made a lot out of the temperature rise.  Although it bears pointing out- it wasn't as if the 8th Army, Desert Rats and Rommel's Afrikakorps took a summer holiday when the temperatures rocketed in 1942.  Personally, I don't believe it'll be a huge issue- our respective forces will operate at night I think Kad, when the already vast technological edge we have will become insurmountable.  I don't care how well-trained the Republican guard are, lacking basic and essential modern equipment to fight at night will cripple them terribly.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>fact, anything that anyone can do to prolong military action works in the dictator's favor<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Again you say the &quot;dictator's favour&quot;.  And again, I respectfully point out that the type of government Iraq has is irrelevant to the issue we're discussing, which is how to best disarm Iraq.  Whether he's a dictator or not is ultimately immaterial- the stated goal is disarmament not regime change.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>May I remind you of the quote above from Sadamm saying time works in his favor and further saying that in time the US/UK coalition will disintegrate? Can you see the similarity between his quote and yours saying &quot;I don't care how long it takes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No I don't see how it does actually- he may say time works in his favour...that couldn't be further from the truth.  He may put on a brave face in public, but deep down, in his heart of hearts he knows that how long the process of peaceful disarmament lasts will have NO bearing on the final result.  His weapons arsenal is doomed Kad, no matter how long he delays, as long as the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>threat</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of force is imminent he will disarm.  In bits and pieces, perhaps.  Over months rather than weeks, probably.  <br>
<br>
It really does not matter how long it takes, as long as it gets done, and peacefully if possible.  I am saying I don't care how long it takes- Saddam says (erroneously) that time works in his favour.  It clearly doesn't work in his favour in any way for a start, and we're saying two completely different things.  Look carefully at what I said and then consider the game Saddam is playing- his goal is to divide us, how easily you misunderstood the gist of what I said is testament to that success.  We both want the same thing Kad, you just seem to feel for some reason that it has to be resolved tomorrow.  I don't see why we're in a rush at all- there's no deadline of any kind constraining the peaceful route.  ALL that matters is whether the inspectors feel they can continue their work.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You, my dear online friend, are playing the enemy's hand.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Nothing could be further from the truth- his hand holds out the hope that he'll keep his WMD, giving the inspectors more time will not achieve that.  If anything, giving the inspectors more time is more likely, as time goes by to turn Arab opinion against him if he's seen to be resisting the peaceful route this time around.  Kuwait and a number of other arab nations called on him to step down this week- keep the diplomatic pressure up and we might even force him from power without a shot being fired.  Arab opinion is hugely against a war of aggression- if he can be forced from power with that opinion onside, then much disaster could be avoided.  Disarmament is a matter of time- the judge of how much time is needed is not yours, or mine, or President Bush's, nor is it prime minister Blair's.  It's Blix and El-Baradei who should make that decision, independent of any military plans.  That is the only sensible way to proceed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>PS For God's sake don't patronize me with the &quot;Hey Sadam if you're reading this board&quot; bullshit.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The point was to illustrate that posting my opinion on this board has no effect on how people perceive Saddam's tactics.  He is playing for more time, everyone knows that, everyone can see that.  It'll all be for nothing in the end, one way or another.  No politician of importance would read what I posted, and even if they did, they wouldn't change their minds.  It was intended to be facetious, I apologize if it offended <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   As for my posts being too long, no one's forcing anyone to read them, truncation isn't my style.<br>
<br>
The fact remains- you fail to convince me how listening to the inspectors, the experts on the ground, and allowing them the time they've requested is in any way bad.  Disarmament will happen peacefully given time- if they the experts don't feel that at any stage, the military option can always be exercised.  The reverse isn't true at all. When war is declared there's no going back, that option will have to be carried to the end, with all the consequences it entails.  Think about that, all of you.<br>
<br>
