<br>
Yes, I believe Turkey's legally elected parliament voted slightly in favor but not enough for the proposition to go through. You shouldn't be worried though, since the country's military has great influence in the workings of Turkey, and will likely 'advice' the MPs better on which button to press in the re-vote. <br>
<br>
I find it quite ironical that the US seems to face most resistance from the countries with democratic systems, and is quite vocal to complain when their leaders act according to public's wishes. That's democracy in action. You know, the one US declares to be spreading everywhere it can. Only, the problem with democracy is that sometimes it can produce unexpected or unwanted results. Dictatorships are usually much more reliable, one way or another. Might that be why most of the US allies in the Middle-East and Asia are 'friendly dictatorships'? <br>
<br>
I would take the claims of US working for the good of the common Iraqi much more seriously if they were a bit more consistent in their rush to democratize and liberate. I don't see much liberating going on in the poorer parts of Africa, even though things are really nasty in there. In this case, it might be a side product that the surviving Iraqis lead a happier life but then again, probably not. Make no mistake, the upcoming war has nothing to do with welfare of the Iraqi people, nor US homeland security, it's purely a move to secure power in the region, not much unlike what Iraq did to Kuwait back in the 90s. Current plans outline a US military government for Iraq until someone more suitable (read puppet) can be found to govern Iraq. Friendly dictatorship incoming? Even though I'm aware that in the current torrent of propaganda from the US it's near impossible to separate facts from fiction, too many things seem a little out of the picture here.<br>
<br>
Regarding the UN, it saddens me that even people I know to be highly sensible see the UN as some kind of bureaucratic monster where everyone tries to gobble as much benefit as they can. Of course there's part of truth in that but I'd like to see it as a compromise machine, which in my opinion is preferable to the alternative, which would likely be some kind of strong-arm politics. If you want to see where <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>machtpolitik</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> leads, see Europe in the first half of the 20th century. That's why I resent the emerging hard-line trend in the US which might be caricaturized as &quot;We do what we want, and you'd better be with us, because if you don't we'll do it to you next.&quot; Future will tell how this will turn out, but with an attitude like that, the US will be picking it's future allies from a scarce supply.<br>
