My contention about US isolationism is that it CONTRIBUTED to the great depression.  Not the primary cause.  Of which, there were multiple.  In 1930, the Hoover administration passed the Smoot-Hawley Tariff act which was the most protectionist isolationist legislation in US History, causing an international trade war.  Problem here, is that agricultural products, wines, beverages, wool, cloth, consumable goods and commodities were affected.  Automobiles that require 800 imported parts were affected.  60,000 people employed in US plants making cheap clothing out of imported wool went jobless.  If foreigners cannot sell their goods in the US, then they cannot earn the dollars they need to buy US exports.  People lose jobs, and new jobs are not reappearing.  This makes the recession turn into a depression.  So yes, I think a US isolationist policy is bad.<br>
